{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778714410,"nonce":"+5YvMxzMtzD1R3MkrLrP7+scFQs=","title":"Deterministic / declarative standard-analysis pipeline for matrix experiments","message":"Every new matrix experiment (b399efc, f47abb1, 2bc95fd, 3702f54, and ahead) goes through the same standard analysis set:\n\n- forward_velocity_profiles (per-cell, go-aligned, pooled trial mean with band, shared y-axes)\n- hold_drift_profiles (per-cell)\n- peak_velocity_distributions (per-trial per cell)\n- summary_metrics (per-cell scalar bars: within-cell vel-RMSE, peak velocity, time-to-peak-after-go, hold drift)\n- training_loss + training_loss_per_term (per-cell trajectories)\n- (sometimes) rmse_ratio_comparison when matched-control structure exists\n\nPlus a `notes/variance_analysis.md` (or `matrix_results.md`) with headline metric tables.\n\n**Current cost**: each new matrix needs an analysis script written largely from scratch by an Opus agent (`analyse_lit_replication_6cell.py` for f47abb1, `analyse_anti_anticipation_6cell_variance.py` for 2bc95fd, `analyse_pregomatrix.py` for 3702f54, now `analyse_movement_ramp_matrix.py` for b399efc). Each script is ~600-1000 lines, ~80% identical between experiments, and a typical dispatch burns ~200k tokens just to regenerate the boilerplate.\n\n**What actually varies between experiments**:\n- The list of cells (variant names + display names)\n- The set of hyperparameters that differ (for legend/labeling)\n- Occasionally a custom plot (e.g. `combo_hold_motor_diagnostic` for 2bc95fd) — but the standard set is unchanged\n\n**Proposed approach**: extract the standard analysis pipeline into a declarative function in `src/rlrmp/analysis/` (call it something like `run_standard_matrix_analysis(experiment, cells, custom_topics=...)`). Each new experiment script becomes a ~30-line config file that:\n1. Declares the cell list (`variant -\u003e display_name -\u003e hyperparameter overrides`)\n2. Calls the declarative pipeline\n3. Optionally adds custom-topic blocks for experiment-specific diagnostics\n\nLibrary entry-point handles: model loading, ensemble eval, go-cue alignment, the 6 standard topic emissions (via `feedbax.plot.save_figure` with `experiment=\u003chash\u003e`), metric computation, `update_marked_section`-based notes update.\n\n**Use feedbaxs existing declarative analysis system if possible.** Feedbax already has analysis primitives that may fit the shape (worth checking `feedbax.plot` and `feedbax.analysis` modules in develop). The declarative-config style would also be compatible with how figure-spec.json is structured (one experiment-level config that emits multiple topic specs).\n\n**Trade-off**: when an experiment legitimately needs analysis beyond the standard set, the experiment script extends the declarative call with custom blocks. The standard set covers ~80% of cases; custom diagnostics for the remaining ~20% stay experiment-specific.\n\n**Migration path** (rough sketch — not commit to one approach yet):\n1. Audit the 4 existing analysis scripts to identify the actually-shared logic vs experiment-specific quirks\n2. Extract shared logic to `src/rlrmp/analysis/matrix.py` (or wherever fits the capability naming)\n3. Rewrite one of the existing experiments (probably f47abb1 since its the most-current template) using the declarative pipeline; verify figures bit-identical\n4. Migrate the other 3 in subsequent commits\n5. Going forward, every new matrix experiment uses the declarative entry-point\n\n**Constraints**:\n- Shared y-axes across cells: enforced by `rlrmp.viz.profile_grids.profile_comparison_grid` (default `shared_yaxes=all`). The declarative pipeline must route through this helper.\n- Capability-named modules: pipeline lives in `src/rlrmp/analysis/`, NOT a `\u003cphase\u003e_helpers.py`-style module.\n- Auto-generated note sections: use `rlrmp.io.update_marked_section` for the metric tables in `notes/*.md`.\n- `align_trials`/`pooled_trial_mean_with_band` are already in place (`Bug: 06f7faf`).\n\n**Why important**: ~200k tokens × ~4 matrices done this year × 2026 matrices ahead = significant ongoing cost; and each agent-rewrite is an opportunity for the bug-fix patches (go-cue alignment, shared y-axes, trim, auto-section markers) to drift between experiments.\n\nSurfaced from rlrmp b399efc deployment session 2026-05-13.\n\nCross-ref: `4d38c15` (project analyses coordination).","files":null}]}